Introduction¶

21st Century Americans are facing an increasingly politicized landscape, with norms and conventions being challenged at every turn. One of the most resoundingly partisan issues is the subject of gun ownership. American gun ownership is protected under the 2nd Amendment of the Constitution, but is with greater frequency being questioned in light of seemingly increasing violence. This is a contentious political issue, often with impassioned arguments on either side of the aisle. This report attempts to set aside partisan notions to as objectively as possible address trends based on accessible data.

One source of gun data is the Federal Bureau of Investigation's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. In their own words:

The National Instant Criminal Background Check System, or NICS, is all about saving lives and protecting people from harmby not letting guns fall into the wrong hands. It also ensures the timely transfer of firearms to eligible gun buyers.

Mandated by the Brady Handgun Violence Prevention Act of 1993 and launched by the FBI on November 30, 1998, NICS is used by Federal Firearms Licensees (FFLs) to instantly determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms. Before ringing up the sale, cashiers call in a check to the FBI or to other designated agencies to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isnt otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. More than 230 million such checks have been made, leading to more than 1.3 million denials. [1]

Pairing this dataset with a dataset of census data will allow us to begin to formulate hypotheses about how a proxy for gun sales and demographics interact. This data can be useful to determine a baseline set of statistics about the basics of guns in America, such as whether gun registration is rising or declining, which states have the highest rate of gun registration, and, how gun registration is affected by levels of income/poverty.

It should be stressed that none of these claims can be made with any amount of certainty and may only provide correlational and not causational trends. In order to make claims with a high degree of fidelity and vigor, hypothesis testing or regression analysis would have to be used.

It has become clear that data cleaning will require deliberation. There are 12,485 rows but in some cases only a few hundred actual data entries. Many of those entries, presumably, are zeros. There are also 55 unique values for states when there are only 50 states in the US (the other five values are the Mariana Islands, Guam, Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, and District of Columbia) so the extra 5 values will most likely be dropped. The data also appears to be organized by prepawn, redemptions, returns,rentals, etc. One way to to parse the data may be to collate the data by these macro categories. It might also be worthwhile to not consider categories that most likely aren't sales related, like returns or rentals.

Immediately, the "Fact" column jumps out as one that will need to be cleaned. The "Fact" column contains the category the census is attempting to measure (population size, population percent change, etc.) and also contains the data range. These will need to be seperated in order to match appropriate statistics from the census data to the gun data by date or month. These Fact Note data seem specific only to a few rows or potentially footnotes at the end of the dataset. It might be best to either remove these or note these values in other places in the dataset. Unlike the gundata set, there are duplicates we will need to address.

Of course, we also want to see how the 'Facts' are arranged and what we can study the data with.

Data Cleaning¶

Gun Data¶

The first order of business will be to clean the Gun Data set. The dataset is very spotty, with many missing fields and empty values. In an attempt to preserve some integrity of the dataset, cleaning should be as minimal as possible. That said, some fields can confidently be cleaned. First is dropping the five values that are territories and not part of the 50 states (the Mariana Islands, Guam, Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, and District of Columbia).

In [11]:
# After discussing the structure of the data and any problems that need to be
#   cleaned, perform those cleaning steps in the second part of this section.

#Drop the five values discussed above
gun_data = gun_data[gun_data.state != 'Guam']
gun_data = gun_data[gun_data.state != 'District of Columbia']
gun_data = gun_data[gun_data.state != 'Mariana Islands']
gun_data = gun_data[gun_data.state != 'Virgin Islands']
gun_data = gun_data[gun_data.state != 'Puerto Rico']

# Check values are dropped

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

It is recommended that you be systematic with your approach. Look at one variable at a time, and then follow it up by looking at relationships between variables.

What State has the highest gun registration? The lowest?¶

It appears that Texas has the largest amount of handguns registered at roughly 600,000 guns, comes in second for long guns and other guns, and leads in multiple gun purchases (as would be expected by those metrics). By contrast, Hawaii seems to have the least registration in all categories accept 'other guns', of which it is the third least registration. This could be evident of lower sales, but it could also be representative of laxer legislation concernign registration. Thus these findings must not be taken as indicative of gun purchases or representative of the population's attitudes towards guns or gun legislation.

Has gun registration gone up or down with time? Are there milestones (spikes or dips in the time-series data)?¶

Some interesting trends can be seen in the above graphs. Firstly, Handguns spike periodically but still show an upward trajectory in baseline, meaning there is a clear rise in handgun registration. Long Gun registration is similarly period, but does not have the upward baseline trend, indicating that long gun registration is somewhat stable. The other gun category only seems to have bee a relativley recent addition to the NICS background check, appearing for the first time in around 2009. This trend seems to be rising, but has the least values associated with it so can not be held to the same rigor as the insight provided from the other trends. Lastly, the multiple gun registration trends shows a relatively stable trend up until around 2007/2008 when it spikes to a high of 50,000 and has periodic but nonetheless arresting levels of registration. Prior to 2007, there appears to be no instance of multiple gun registrations upwards of 20,000 but post-2007 multiple gun registrations of 20,000 occur seemingly at least once a year.

Conclusions¶

As mentioned through out the project, none of these findings are scientific or rigorous. These findings have not been proven through rigorous hypothesis or regression testing and should not be taken as valid. One of the most frustrating aspects to this analysis was the amount of missing data. The most clear example is the Other Gun vs. Time graph, which shows how the the other gun data was seemingly only trended 12 or so years after the NICS was established. I am not alone in my frustration witht he incomplete data as there is even a movement to identify and correct the NICS dataset called FixtheNICS. A corollary that comes with the 'Other Gun vs. Time' graph is how there is no mention of how data collection methodologies changed through the years. In the analysis, I looked to the 'Multiple Gun vs. Time' and saw a clear difference in trending before and after 2007. Could this be due to a more accurate data colleciton method? Unfortunately, unlike the census data, the NICS dataset is not as well annotated.

That said, certain exploratory hypotheses can be formulated at this stage, such as "Handgun registration is rising over time" or "Multiple gun registrations increased after 2007."
